#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:1
msgid "Reserving syntax"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:3
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:5
msgid ""
"`any_identifier#`, `any_identifier\"...\"`, and `any_identifier'...'` are "
"now reserved syntax, and no longer tokenize."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:7
msgid ""
"This is mostly relevant to macros. E.g. `quote!{ #a#b }` is no longer "
"accepted."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:8
msgid ""
"It doesn't treat keywords specially, so e.g. `match\"...\" {}` is no longer "
"accepted."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:9
msgid ""
"Insert whitespace between the identifier and the subsequent `#`, `\"`, or "
"`'` to avoid errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:11
msgid "Edition migrations will help you insert whitespace in such cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:13
msgid "Details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:15
msgid ""
"To make space for new syntax in the future, we've decided to reserve syntax "
"for prefixed identifiers and literals: `prefix#identifier`, "
"`prefix\"string\"`, `prefix'c'`, and `prefix#123`, where `prefix` can be any "
"identifier. (Except those prefixes that already have a meaning, such as "
"`b'...'` (byte strings) and `r\"...\"` (raw strings).)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:22
msgid ""
"This provides syntax we can expand into in the future without requiring an "
"edition boundary. We may use this for temporary syntax until the next "
"edition, or for permanent syntax if appropriate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:26
msgid ""
"Without an edition, this would be a breaking change, since macros can "
"currently accept syntax such as `hello\"world\"`, which they will see as two "
"separate tokens: `hello` and `\"world\"`. The (automatic) fix is simple "
"though: just insert a space: `hello \"world\"`. Likewise, `prefix#ident` "
"should become `prefix #ident`. Edition migrations will help with this fix."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:32
msgid ""
"Other than turning these into a tokenization error, [the RFC](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/3101) does not attach a meaning to any prefix yet. "
"Assigning meaning to specific prefixes is left to future proposals, which "
"will now—thanks to reserving these prefixes—not be breaking changes."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:37
msgid ""
"Some new prefixes you might potentially see in the future (though we haven't "
"committed to any of them yet):"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:40
msgid ""
"`k#keyword` to allow writing keywords that don't exist yet in the current "
"edition. For example, while `async` is not a keyword in edition 2015, this "
"prefix would've allowed us to accept `k#async` in edition 2015 without "
"having to wait for edition 2018 to reserve `async` as a keyword."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:45
msgid ""
"`f\"\"` as a short-hand for a format string. For example, `f\"hello "
"{name}\"` as a short-hand for the equivalent `format!()` invocation."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:48
msgid "`s\"\"` for `String` literals."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:50
msgid "`c\"\"` or `z\"\"` for null-terminated C strings."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:55
msgid "Migration"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:57
msgid ""
"As a part of the 2021 edition a migration lint, "
"`rust_2021_prefixes_incompatible_syntax`, has been added in order to aid in "
"automatic migration of Rust 2018 codebases to Rust 2021."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:59
msgid ""
"In order to have `rustfix` migrate your code to be Rust 2021 Edition "
"compatible, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2021/reserving-syntax.md:65
msgid ""
"Should you want or need to manually migrate your code, migration is fairly "
"straight-forward."
msgstr ""

